    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-29T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-29T21:00:00-05:00" n="705"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d705">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10897: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-30T11:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 30, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 30—2:11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>502. Department’s 273, October 29, 1 p.m.<note n="80" xml:id="d705fn80">See
                        footnote 77, above.</note> Discreet approach reveals that the German Embassy
                    has received no information that any discussion of the character suggested by
                    the Associated Press despatch has taken place between the German and Japanese
                    Ambassadors in China. It is also revealed that the relations between the two <pb
                        facs="0656" n="649" xml:id="pg_649"/> Ambassadors had not been “very
                    satisfactory” owing to the employment by China of German military instructors
                    and also to Japanese suspicion that Trautmann<note n="81" xml:id="d705fn81"
                        >German Ambassador in China.</note> is “pro-Chinese” and that Trautmann took
                    advantage of a recent visit to Shanghai to improve his relations with
                        Kawagoe<note n="82" xml:id="d705fn82">Japanese Ambassador in China.</note>
                    (see our 464, October 9, 9 p.m.).</p>
                <p>The German Military Attaché is to return from Shanghai and the German Embassy has
                    offered to give us any further information on this matter which he may
                    bring.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
